Peter Englund's emotionally powerful new book called Beauty and Grief: The First World War (The Beauty and the Sorow: An Intimate History of the First World War) begins with such a long list of emerging characters as your head turns.
One piece of advice on how to behave at this point: carefully pull this page out and make a backup of it.
For all persons, in Mr Englund's novel story, you will get to know each other very well, and this list will serve you as a navigation - like a beacon - in moments when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in various situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards Nobel Prize for literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author describes it himself, quite fittingly, as an "antihistoric work".
It contains a number of well-known names, important contracts or famous battles, and, on the contrary, there is almost a lack of ambassadors, energetic journalists, and debates on tactics and equipment.
It's not even a book about what happened, the author explains, as more of a "book of what it was like." It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beautiful and sorrowful" combines war experiences of 20 more fewer fat men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, rescue drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, lose their minds or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in the church - new ones join the complex of fates while others put out.
Mr. Englund's book differs from classical historical novels.
It regulates the idea that the first world war was just a terrible burial battle in the West Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with bee nests falling on them, have to spend Christmas in the shadow of pyramids or face the presence of much tse-tse.
It's almost a very touching reading from the beginning.
War will consume people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When the gunfire starts in the distance and you're the woman who's at home with your kids, are you gonna run away or are you gonna stay?
Who's coming?
Almost nobody understands what's going on, even why the whole war was fought.
"The vacuum created by the lack of facts," Mr Englund noted, "was filled with speculations, assumptions, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and fears."
"Beauty and sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are all taken from resumes, letters and other published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound frightening and entrenched, but the integration of small moments and details makes them absolutely alive and credible.
Many of them discuss suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Remarkables, all over the place."
"Coffin substitute, aluminium copy, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It goes further and describes the substitutes for food in Germany.
It refers to "masses made from pressed rice cooked in Skopje fat (and supplemented with fake wood bone), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato dumplings, boots with wooden soles".
It mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
