There is an American in him who has an inner instinct for savagery and brutality, and he declares about war: "You will finally understand that this is what human nature is. No sitting in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, evening newspapers or a good book and pretending that this mask of yours represents civilization and that there is no barbar behind this starched self in the interior."
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon, and no one will even notice, let alone grieve.
"When one finally accepts the sacrifice, at least one would expect it to happen before the eyes of the grateful audience," he writes.
Instead, he feels like a "convict he hangs secretly".
Other comments relate to the departure of old Europe and the onset of new horrors.
"Conflict was becoming more and more an economic competition and a competitive battle," writes Mr Englund, "a war between factories."
