The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has launched research on the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for obesity of children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to reveal the gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research called "Genetics of Obesity in Children and Youth" will enable you to obtain results on overweight.
In a report by the head of the Research Medical Unit in the field of biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Centre of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team composed of doctors, nurses, nutrition experts and social workers had been set up.
The team relies on the support of specialists and students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Political Institute (IPN).
Involve in research can also be a wide public, whether or not authorized. People can come to participating IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where youth tests will be conducted every Saturday from 8 o'clock.
He stressed that research started at the Cuahtémoc Sports Centre (Mexico State) and since 8 October this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualcóolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
As soon as data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Centre (in the south of the Federal District) and eventually at the Morelos Sports Centre (north from the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of obesity development and to identify risk factors on Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and the family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He pointed out that anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist area), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined, and genes are examined (they are trying to identify genes that are involved in child obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects the concerns of health professionals over the alarming rise in child weight.
'A health survey carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that only 77% and 47% of obesity in boys occurred in just six years, and 47% in girls. The dramatic increase also occurred in overweight', according to an IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is that the country's population differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African, and this is reflected in genes responsible for diabetes and overweight.
He explained that generally the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calorie) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The investigator explained that the direct benefit of participants is that they will be given an overall assessment of the condition of children, thereby finding out whether they exhibit any known overweight or obesity.
He said that even the presence of dark color spatter (acanthosis) on the neck and forearms suggests that the individual will likely suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetic conditions.
The information is confidential so far, the doctors are handing it over to the parents in writing and explaining to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order to avoid their children’s disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary life-style which means a lack of daily physical activity, day-long exposure to television and the use of means of transport instead of walking at short distances.
Overweight is also caused by large calorie intake, it is a higher consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and a genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
In Asfalt, UNAM will not be crying
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, creates modified asphalts with polymers and creates a mixture with better functionality, independent of climate conditions and temperature
If it was to care for well-being, it would not be necessary to correct nearly 200 000 embankments after each rainy period in the Valle de México Metropolitan Region, said Rafael Herrera Najere, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemical (FQ) of UNAM, who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt deposits were adequate, there would be a significant restriction of prayers, or even it would be possible to completely eliminate them.
In his lecture, the technological cause of pomegranates, which he carried out in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his direction develops modified polymer asphalts, which should produce a mixture of similar characteristics as asphalt, but also greater mechanical resistance, both at low and at high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely hot climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country.
He explained that asphalt, the hardest part of oil, is a group of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a large molecular mass called asphaltines, and other low molecular weights called maltenes. Together, they supply asphalt with a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, behaves like liquid, at 120 degrees high viscosity, and at 50 degrees it is almost stable, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, an expert on chemical engineering noted.
A scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México were covered with a flexible tile, consisting of six layers of materials, three of which were mixed with asphalt.
Among the highest layers is an asphalt cartridge, made up of small stones covered in asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that forms the cartridge is filled with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is so possible that the forces in the board are well distributed.
If it were modified asphalt, it would be even better to disintegrate, a chemical engineer would assume.
He added that the last layer of the coat, made of fine stones, would be placed on the asphalt cartridge, also covered in asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the vehicle rails, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt cartridge and must ensure the friction of the vehicle.
Since a heavy load will be exposed as part of the longing, the coat must have sufficient thickness and must be alert to the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a major impact on the functionality of the asphalt cartridge.
