Nord Stream, new port of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline connecting directly to Eastern Europe to Russia and running at the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to work.
It must supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, including 4 of them Heads of State and Government, took part last Tuesday in the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that will connect directly between Russia and Germany under the sea.
Symbolically German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the controlling valve controlling Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
This new gas pipeline will start every year to Western Europe with 27,5 billion additional cubic metres of Russian gas with the first pipeline of 1,224 km connecting the region of Petrograd to the federal country of Mecklembursko-Pomorjany.
The second pipe, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will allow for the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, a quantity equal to the entire French consumption.
And it's already reminded of the possibility of building a third pipeline pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the early completion of this huge building is the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested the project.
Nord Stream will in fact allow the gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being driven by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats of shutting down access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed it most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet Pact", with an appeal to the Alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means saying it's a politically sensitive topic.
Western Europe gained greater confidence in its purchases through its support for this Russian project.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project has created rifts between Europeans from the east and west.
Russia has barely managed to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western states with high gas consumption, whose bearings are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us," François Fillon confirmed at the opening ceremony of this pipeline and demonstrated at what point the big gas contracts of things are both political and economic.
All of this explains the wide smiles of the leaders of Gazprom present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
Submarine pipes are made of steel fitted with concrete cloaks to protect against anchors of seagoing vessels.
It consists of an average depth of 200 m at the bottom of the sea.
Its construction had to be avoided by minefields from World War II.
"For safety, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures to protect fauna and flora had to be increased as well.
The pipe itself is a long metal hose weighing as 242 Eiffelworks, which is nowhere to be interrupted by valves or maintenance stations throughout its length.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leader rejected it when the Swedes were only a little eager to see Russia's state society, as it permanently settled on their coast.
"In the event of a malfunction, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute", says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline shall escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, because the welding was designed to create intrusion once every 100,000 years.
The external gas control is carried out by a submarine robot hauled by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This unit of cigar shape with a diameter of 1 metre is introduced inside the pipe and is pushed by gas.
The target shall be provided with accurate information on any deformation of metal parts throughout the three days of the journey at a speed of 3 m/s.
The next pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to make the slightest correction.
The gas circulation is simply secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar on start and 100 bar on target.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
The head of the position remains Gazprom, which holds 51%.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunia and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company has a headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased this company for five years through a contract which can be renewed, all its capacity for gas transport.
"Gazprom will have a profit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of actual gas delivered," says Jens Müller.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was ensured by 30% of shareholders and 70% of bank loans.
Total labour costs should reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez group, the investment costs went up to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be returned to them, because the only risk they take is Gazprom.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves of a height of 4,5 meters form an output gate of gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before being transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving 1 million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
When reaching full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
