There are still unspoken ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that the managers questioned had a "weak level of knowledge about handicapped persons" with "exceeding the idea of persons in a wheelchair and psychological or mental disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the goal of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The last known figures from 2008 give a status equal to 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, charged with collecting fees from businesses that do not comply with this law.
The number of "punished" enterprises is evidence, as is the amount paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 more guilty companies to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in big businesses."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
